Make the unification logic in extendCompoundSelector more like the original libsass implementation since we're trusting that they've implemented unify_with correctly.
Realized we were missing an extra level of nesting for the datastructures involved in the extend, so I typedef'd a ComplexSelectorDequeDeque and updated the code to use it.
Fixed selector ordering bug. I called push_back when I should have called push_front to keep the original original compound selector at the beginning of the list.

First pass of implementing trim. This won't do the right thing yet until sources is set in extendCompoundSelector. The 182_test_nested_extend_loop sass-spec test requires trim to pass.

First pass of adding sources to the compound selectors during extend. This makes sass-spec's 182_test_nested_extend_loop test pass. When debugging that test, I'm seeing the correct sources in all but one case. It happens to work anyway by chance.
Commenting out some prints to make it less verbose. Removing some outdated comments.

Removing extendRulesetOld, our first pass implementation of the extend operator based on the documentation only. We did not have a full understanding of the algorithm at the time. The newer code is handling a lot more cases correctly, so this code isn't needed anymore.

Cleaning up printing to the terminal. The order of arguments to print helper methods are now consistent. The default behavior is now the most common (printing with a newline by default). I also took a pass at removing some unneeded debugging prints and commented out code to make the code easier to understand.

More clean up. Renamed printSelectors to printComplexSelectorDeque to be consistent with the other printing helper methods which are named after the datastructures they print. Continued to remove commented out or unused code. Standardized on putting comments with the ruby code just above the function instead of inside of it so you can easily see the function signature when working in the function.
Removing the old extend operator code since I don't think we need it for immediate reference any more. We can always look at master if we want to see it.
This should all be commenting and clarity fixes. There should be no functional changes with this commit.
First pass of subweave implementation. Needs a lot of clean up. I didn't want to spend a lot of time on that until I got it working in a basic case (which it doesn't now).
Renamed print to match ruby sass printing I'm doing. Just committing since I need to change branches.

Fixing sass-spec 010_test_multiple_extends_with_multiple_extenders_and_single_target. We were not properly comparing selectors when putting them into our collection. We relied on Complex_Selector operator less than, but it was simply doing a string comparision. This doesn't treat .a.b the same as .b.a, but we need that behavior since that's closer to what ruby sass does. The fix was to implement operator== for Complex_Selector, Compound_Selector, and Simple_Selector. We compare Complex_Selector and Compound_Selector similarly to how ruby sass does. We still use string comparision for Simple_Selector.

Fix 216_test_nested_sibling_extend and 217_test_parent_and_sibling_extend. trim was allowing extra duplicate selectors to come through. The main issue was that the ruby code used Array.equal, which was checking if the selectors were the exact same object. This worked because they did a shallow copy of the array, which kept the same objects in both. When porting this, we did a deep comparison of the array, which gave different results. We clone our equivalent of the array, so we can't see if the objects are the same objects. However, we can just keep track of iteration indices and compare them to skip comparing an object against itself.

Fix for trim to properly skip comparing against the same sequence. Use toTrimIndex == resultIndex && seqs1 == seqs2 instead of toTrimIndex == resultIndex. toTrimIndex == resultIndex was introduced to fix a bug where ruby is doing object comparison instead of equivalency comparisions. What I didn't realize was that result gets written to during the iteration, and we do want to compare if the object has changed. So, try checking both. I'm not 100 percent sure this is the right fix, but it makes a lot of tests pass. Committing for now, and I'll noodle on it tomorrow.

This is mainly to get our printing to match up with ruby sass, which is why it is debug only. ruby sass only runs extend on selectors with extensions. However, libsass runs it on all selectors. support colliding CSS filter effects functionsCSS filter effects [0] define several functions (invert, grayscale,nopacity, saturation) that collide with the names of built-in Sassnfunctions. Overload these functions with a no-op when the filter effectsnfunction signature is discovered. This is compatible with Ruby Sass.nnFor example, calling `invert` with a color will return an inverted colornas before:nncolor: invert(#333) => color: #ccccccnnBut calling `invert` with a percentage will pass through the functionncall unharmed.nnfilter: invert(30%) => filter: invert(30%)nfilter: invert(.03) => filter: invert(.03)nnFixes #151.nn[0]: http://www.w3.org/TR/filter-effects/n
prefer gray to grey when converting colors to namesFor consistency with Sass.n

inspect: always round color channels before inspectionSince RGB channels are stored as doubles, HSL/RGB conversions can resultnin decimal values being stored for a channel. This breaks color namenlookup. For example, previouslynnrgb(127.5, 127.5, 127.5)nnwould fail to be converted to gray, despite being rounded and outputnasnn#808080nnwhich *does* map to gray. So instead of performing the rounding onlynwhen outputting as a hex triplet, perform the rounding at the start,nalways. This achieves consistency with Sass.n

MemoryManager: Use free instead of delete.On instantiating `Color` at src/functions.cpp (`BUILT_IN(rgba_4)` body)n, `Memory_Manager`'s `operator new()` is called which after explicitlyncalling the underlying `operator new(size_t)`, `static_cast` thenallocated memory for `void*` -> `AST_Node*` conversion.nnThe `delete` operator in `Memory_Manager` is called when an exceptionnis thrown during the construction of the object (right after the `new`)n. When calling underlying `delete` from custom `delete` implementation,nit throws access violation probably because it tries to `delete` allncontinents of objects which weren't initialised properly, as in case ofninvalid rgba value, `error_handling` layer throws.nnTherefore, more rawer `free()` is used to avoid `bad_alloc`<->`delete`npanics. :)nnNote that this is the quick fix to the problem. The actual fix would bento implement a custom exception-tolerant `New`.nnRead more on this subject:nhttp://www.scs.stanford.edu/~dm/home/papers/c++-new.html.nnFixes #1443.n

Don't allocate std::random_device staticallyIt appears that on Linux with gcc (tested with gcc 4.6.3 on Ubuntu 12.04 andngcc 5.2.1 on Ubuntu 15.10) std::random_device will open /dev/urandom, and keepnthe file open for the lifetime of the std::random_device object.nnSince libsass allocates the std::random_device globally, it will not bendestroyed if the processes execs. Futhermore std::random_device does not setnclose-on-exec on the fd, so the fd will be leaked to the child process.nnThe std::random_device object is only used by the GetSeed function, and as thenGetSeed function is only called once to seed the rand variable, there is nonneed to keep the std::random_device object.nnSo this patch moves the std::random_device object into the GetSeed function,nthereby eliminating the fd-leak.n

Fix issue when using intermediate string returnsIn MSVC the following can lead to segfault:nsass_copy_c_string(stream.str().c_str());nReason is that the string returned by str() is disposed beforensass_copy_c_string is invoked. The string is actually a stacknobject, so indeed nobody is holding on to it. So it seemsnperfectly fair to release it right away. So the const char*nby c_str will point to invalid memory. I'm not sure if this isnthe behavior for all compiler, but I'm pretty sure we wouldnhave gotten more issues reported if that would be the case.nWrapping it in a functions seems the cleanest approach as thenfunction must hold on to the stack variable until it's done.n

Handle fake parent selectors when evalingLibSass fully parses selectors during the parsing stage. This isndifferent from Ruby Sass which parse selectors and string duringnthe parsing stage, and lazily eval'ing when required. Thisndifference causes some pathological selector issues. Our eagernparsing of selectors has resulted in us hacking in faken`Parent_Selector` into `Sequence_Selector` during parsing.nnThese fake `Parent_Selector` play havoc with `resolve_parent_refs`nwhen within `@at-root` blocks. I spent a couple weeks going downnthe rabbit whole of refactoring our selector parsing to be lazy beforenbailing.nnExplicitly marking which `Parent_Selector` are fake during parsingnallows us faithfully implement the `implicit_parent` flag inn`resolve_parent_refs`.nnFixes #2006nFixes #2198nSpec sass/sass-spec#936n

Thisnvalue is prepended to the individual entries in the u00e2u0080u009csourceu00e2u0080u009d field.nLine 5: A list of original sources used by the u00e2u0080u009cmappingsu00e2u0080u009d entry.nLine 6: An optional list of source content, useful when the u00e2u0080u009csourceu00e2u0080u009dncanu00e2u0080u0099t be hosted. The contents are listed in the same order as thensources in line 5. u00e2u0080u009cnullu00e2u0080u009d may be used if some original sources shouldnbe retrieved by name.nLine 7: A list of symbol names used by the u00e2u0080u009cmappingsu00e2u0080u009d entry.nLine 8: A string with the encoded mapping data.n

Change list definitions to explicitely include delimiters

Change the parser to recognize bracketed lists.This is the idea: in the same way the old parser looks for parenthesisndelimiters, let's add another case for brackets delimiters.nnIn case an open bracket is found, the parser will look for a list. Therenare three possible results of parsing a list:nnFirst, the parsed expression is not a list at all. libsass parser tendsnto avoid wrapping if lists are only one item lists. But bracketed listsnprevent unwrapping so the item becomes the solely item for a newnbracketed list.nnExample:nsingleton-item --> [ singleton-item ]nnSecond, the list is indeed a list with some explicit delimiter. Thisncase is similar to the previous one. Brackets prevent unwrapping so thisntime is the list as a whole which become the unique item of thenbracketed list.nnExample:n(item1, item2, ...) --> [ (item1, item2, ...) ]n[item1, item2, ...] --> [ [item1, item2, ...] ]nnThird, the list is a list with no delimiters. So its items actuallynbelong to the bracketed list. The parse will fix the delimiter of thenlist for them to be brackets.nnExample:nSuppose | ... | stands for a list with no delimiters.n|item1, item2, ...|  --> [item1, item2, ...]n
Copying the delimiter property also.Functions operating on a copy of lists must copy the delimiter also.n

Modifying emitter to take brackets into account.First, instead of directly writting the left or right parenthesisncharacters, now functions are called for left or right delimitersnand change in case of parenthesis or brackets.nnSecond, in case of bracketed list, always add the brackets. Also addncomma in case it is a one-item comma-separate list. Otherwise it wouldnbecome a one-item space-separated list.nnThird, libsass prevent from emitting invisible items. Thus, an emptynspace / comma separated list won't be printed at all but bracketednlist are never invisible, event the empty ones.n

Add fast casting for classes that are finalCleaning up a few static casts on the way.nnDue to the new unified way to cast nodes, we can nowneasily introduce a way to have a faster up-casting fornclasses we know are final. This is done in a centralizednway. You simply keep calling `Cast` to up-cast to a morenspecific type. The compiler will automatically choose thenfaster type-id check, if the involving class is final. Wenhave to produce the list of the classes that act as basesnby hand. It turned out to be the much shorter list thannlisting all final classes. Maybe the compiler could deducenthis information from a final keyword on the class, but hisnapproach seems safe and accomplishes the job either way.nnFTR: Performance profiling showed that dynamic cast canntake up around 20% of the whole runtime. So having fasterncasts for classes we now are safe seems to be a good thing.nHaving its configuration centralized makes it also veryneasy to maintain and regular code does not need to worry!n

Remove -undefined error, --no-undefined LDFLAGSAs far as I can tell, `-undefined error` was introduced mistakenlynto replace `--no-undefined`, which doesn't work Apple's cctools' ld.nThe problem is, `-undefined error` _only_ works on cctools' ld.nThis is much less noticeable than the original problem, because GCC's ldnwon't complain, it just won't do the right thing. The Solaris linker, onnthe other hand, _will_ complain:nnld: fatal: file error: open failed: No such file or directorynnThis is a misleading error message, but what it is actually telling usnis that it can't open a file named error, which it tries to do becausenit doesn't recognise -undefined as an option that can take annargument.nnWe can demonstrate that this doesn't have the desired effect in GCC too.nConsider this a C source file, main.c, containing the following:nnextern void hello(void);nnint main(void) {nhello();n}nnIf we compile this using the command `gcc -fPIC -shared main.c`, wenwill get no indication that the `hello` function we are trying to callnhas never been defined. This is for, as the GCC documentation puts it,nhistorial reasons.nnIf we don't want this, we can pass `--no-undefined` to the linker, likenthis:nngcc -fPIC -shared -Wl,--no-undefined main.cnnThis is what the Makefile used to do, before being changed. Running thisncommand will produce an error informing us of our mistake:nn/tmp/ccGRJkJ8.o: In function `main':nmain.c:(.text+0xc): undefined reference to `hello'ncollect2: error: ld returned 1 exit statusnnHowever, trying to use the cctools' ld's equivalent reveals that GCC'snld definitely does not interpret it the same way. This command willnsucceed, just the same as the one where we specified no explicit linkernoptions at all. I don't want to speculate on what effect, if any,n`-undefined error` has on GCC's ld, but it definitely isn't the rightnone.nnAfter some discussion, we've decided it's best to just remove thesenflags.n

AST: Fix clang warnings, add const, remove virtualMechanical changes:n* Fixes all clang warnings in ast.hpp and removes warnings suppression.n* Adds `const` to a bunch of methods.n* Removes `virtual` where unnecessary.n* Adds `override` where necessary (as part of fixing clang warnings).nnNon-mechanical changes:n* Removes unused `Thunk` class.n* Makes `hash()` const by marking `hash_` as `mutable` (implementation detail).n* Makes `first()` and `last()` const, and adds `mutable_first()` and `mutable_first()`n  for the rare cases where mutability is necessary.n* `Complex_Selector` internally now uses `tail_` and `head_` directlyn  instead of going through accessors (these accessors create a `SharedImpl` on every call).n

Avoid modifying Expression in ast_node_to_sass_valuePreviously, the argument to `ast_node_to_sass_value` was a `const Expression_Ptr`.nnThe `const` there was useless, as it didn't mean the constness of Expression but merely that `val` pointer could not be reassigned within the function (due to how pointer `typedef` and `const` interacts).nnAssuming the intended argument type was `const Expression_Ptr *`, I've changed it to `Expression_Ptr_Const`.nnThis required splitting `to{RGBA,HSLA}(bool)` into separate functions, so that the one that always copies could be marked as `const`.n

Remove _Ptr(_Const) typedefs (#2847)Removes these typedefs because pointers should be handled with care.rnHaving them visually stand out in the code helps us avoid common pitfalls,rnsuch as accidentally using `Ptr` instead of `Obj`.rnrnThis change has been automatically generated using the following command:rnrn```bashrnfind src ( -name '*.cpp' -o -name '*.hpp' ) -exec sed -i rn'/typedef.*_Ptr[_;]/d;'rn's/([A-Za-z_]*)_Ptr_Const/const 1*/g;'rn's/([A-Za-z_]*)_Ptr/1*/g;'rn's/([a-z])##*/1*/g' '{}' +rn```rnrnFixes #2785
